    "recap_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/news/2026/3/14/baseball-niners-fall-in-middle-game-with-st-john-s",
    "recap_headline": "Charlotte",
    "recap_text": "CHARLOTTE \u2013\nCharlotte Baseball dropped the middle game of its series against St. John's with a 3-2 loss at Hayes Stadium on Saturday afternoon (March 14).\nCharlotte (12-6) had the bases loaded with one out in the eighth inning looking for the tie, but St. John's (7-11) got out of the inning with its 3-2 lead still intact and left CLT's tying run on base again in the ninth inning to take the series over the Green and White.\nRobert Nedry\nand\nAlec DeMartino\n, Charlotte's two and three-hole hitters on Saturday, led the team with two hits apiece while\nSpencer Nolan\n,\nDawson Bryce\n,\nTodd Hudson\n,\nCody Gunderson\n, and\nDylan Koontz\nall had one \u2013 meaning the top seven batters in the lineup had a hit in the game.\nNedry drove in one of Charlotte's two runs while Bryce had the other, hitting a lead-off home run in the second inning for his third homer of the season. Bryce's hit also kept his team-high hitting streak alive at 12 straight games while he and DeMartino extended their on-base streaks to 19 games \u2013 reaching safely in all 18 games this year and in the final game of last season.\nDrew Munn\ngot the start on the mound and tallied three strikeouts in the first 4.2 innings of work while being charged with the first two runs of the game.\nChayse Oxborrow\nwas called on to get a pair of lefties out and did just that before letting\nJoseph Taylor\nfinish the game. Taylor fanned six batters in the final 3.2 frames and allowed one run on three hits and three walks while being Charlotte's pitcher of record in the loss.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nSt. John's opened the scoring in the first inning with a home run over the trees in left field for an early 2-0 lead.\nCharlotte answered in the second inning with a home run of its own when Bryce left the yard. Leading off the frame, Bryce took the second pitch of the inning for a ride over the fence in left to cut the deficit in half.\nThe Niners erased the deficit fully in the next inning when Jimenez came home on a single from Nedry. Jimenez drew a lead-off walk and then moved up to third on a sacrifice bunt and a groundout. CLT's two-out hitting came through again, as Nedry found a hole up the middle to level things up.\nMunn settled in nicely after the first inning, retiring 12 of the final 14 batters he faced. He sat the side down in order in the second and fourth frames and only allowed a single hit in the third and fifth. It was the nine-hole hitter that got the single in the fifth, prompting the Niners to go to the bullpen for the third time through the Red Storm's lineup. Oxborrow was the arm out of the bullpen with two lefties due up and he did his job, getting the final out of the fifth and the first of the sixth before handing it off to Taylor.\nTaylor kept things where they were in the sixth but gave up the lead in the seventh on a pair of hits and a walk.\nCharlotte had a pair on base in the seventh inning but couldn't get a runner past third and had its best chance to tie the game in the eighth with the bases loaded with one out. DeMartino picked up his second hit of the game to start the inning before moving up on a groundout to the right side. A four-pitch walk put a pair on and a single through the left side of the infield loaded them up. However, that was as close as the tying run got as a fielder's choice to first base got the run at the plate on a force out for the second out and a fly ball to left ended the inning.\nTaylor stranded a runner on second with his sixth strikeout of the game to get the offense back up in the ninth inning, but the rally wasn't there. Nolan singled with one out and got as far as second, but a strikeout ended the game and left him there.\nUP NEXT\nThe series wraps up on Sunday (March 15) from The Hayes at noon."
  },
